## Wikipedia:Wikipedia Signpost

This is not an article. It's a signpost, a marker, a rather tedious waypoint on the road to… well, wherever it is we're all pretending to go. Think of it as a particularly uninspired exhibit in a museum of bureaucratic futility. It’s a [redirect](/Wikipedia:Redirect), which, if you're unfamiliar with the concept, means it's a placeholder, a digital echo pointing to something else. A bit like a promise made by a politician.

This particular redirection is categorized, because of course it is. It’s been filed away under [To a project page](/Category:Redirects_to_Wikipedia_project_pages), which is a fancy way of saying it points to a page within the project's own labyrinthine structure. Not a talk page, mind you. Those are for actual discussions, which, let's be honest, are rarely as efficient as a good, solid redirect. It’s a redirect *from* something, *to* something else within the [namespace](/Wikipedia:Namespace) of [project (Wikipedia: or WP:) space](/Wikipedia:Project_namespace). If you're outside this space, you're probably already lost. If you're inside, you're likely just lost in a different, more official-looking way. Redirects from outside the project space are automatically filed under [Category:Redirects to project namespace](/Category:Redirects_to_project_namespace). It’s all very organized, isn't it? Like a well-maintained graveyard.

It also carries the tag [From a short name](/Category:Redirects_from_short_names). This means the title itself is a truncated version of a more elaborate, probably less useful, full title. Like calling someone by their nickname instead of their full, birth-certificate-approved moniker. It’s a shortcut, a convenience, a concession to the fact that most people have the attention span of a gnat on caffeine. So, instead of typing out the full, glorious designation, you can just use the abbreviated version. It’s a redirect from an initialism, specifically, according to the rather precise, and frankly, alarming, instructions, this is not to be tagged with {{[R from initialism](/Template:R_from_initialism)}} or {{[R from abbreviation](/Template:R_from_abbreviation)}}. No, this is for the initials of a person's name. Because apparently, even bureaucratic systems have their favorite forms of shorthand.

And then there’s the matter of [protection levels](/Wikipedia:Protection_policy). The system, in its infinite, automated wisdom, will sense, describe, and categorize these levels. It’s all very transparent, you see. Everything is accounted for, logged, and filed away for posterity. Or at least until the next system update.

So, there you have it. A redirect. A digital nod. A signpost pointing to a signpost. Fascinating, isn't it? If you find this level of meta-commentary thrilling, perhaps you're in the right place. Or perhaps you just need to recalibrate your definition of "thrilling." Either way, don't expect a parade.